      <hedline>
        <hl1>World Briefing | Asia: North Korea: End To Anti-South Broadcasts</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By James Brooke (NYT)</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Brooke, James</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Senior North Korean official Kim Ryong Song announces Voice of National Salvation, North Korean propaganda radio station, will stop broadcasting after over 30 years of airing hostile messages targeted to South Korea (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>After three decades of broadcasting hostile propaganda to South Korea, a North Korean radio station, Voice of National Salvation, will cease broadcasting tomorrow, a senior official promised. In making the promise, the official, Kim Ryong Song, acknowledged that the station was operated by North Korea. Since broadcasts began in 1970, North Korea has said that the station was maintained by an underground Communist cell in South Korea. South Korea's military traced the signals to Haeju, a North Korean city close to the border.</p>
        <p>James Brooke (NYT)</p>
      </block>
